      <text>Universal Quantifier 1</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[Note that the universal quantification of \(Q(x)\) is the statement "\(Q(x)\) for all values of \(x\) in the domain." 
The notation \( \forall x Q(x) \) denotes the universal quantification of \(Q(x)\). An element for which \(Q(x)\) is false is called a <b>counterexample</b> to \(  \forall x Q(x) \).

Let \(Q(x)\) be the statement "\(x + 1 > x.\)"
What is the truth value of the quantification \(  \forall x Q(x) \), where the domain consists of all real numbers? [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]]]></text>
    </questiontext>
